{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"30a32a4f-bf53-4063-81be-19f5a4084698","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2 — here's the modern pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Synchronous init: inject TestContext via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    // Asynchronous init: use [TestInitialize]\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        _service = await MyService.CreateAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public async Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.DisposeAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void Test_Example()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test...\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_service);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor injection** for `TestContext` is the recommended approach in MSTest v3+ (replaces the old property-setter pattern).\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** supports `async Task` — use it for any async setup that must run before each test.\n- **`[ClassInitialize]`** / **`[ClassCleanup]`** are available for one-time async setup at the class level (these are `static` methods).\n- The old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern still works but constructor injection is preferred.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ea2bb0b7-b0b8-4ceb-8aeb-7cd8a115b5b4","outputTokens":358,"requestId":"5800:28CF3A:373502C:3AE9FC1:6A0338AD"},"id":"0b1fde73-248d-4a67-9eae-24196aadaf72","timestamp":"2026-05-12T14:27:05.581Z","parentId":"b89f0ab2-a5ea-4053-a42a-440e5d128d83"}
